{{Orphan|date=June 2018}}
'''Discursive deracialization''' is a term used for the rhetorical removal of '[[Race (human categorization)|race]]' from potentially racially motivated arguments.<ref>Goodman, S., & Burke, S. (2011). Discursive deracialization in talk about asylum seeking. Journal of Community & Applied Social Psychology, 21(2), 111-123. doi:10.1002/casp.1065</ref> Earlier known as "deracialization of discourse",<ref>Reeves, 1983</ref> discursive deracialization is where the opposition to, or negative representations of, minority out-groups is attributed to reasons other than race.<ref>Augoustinos, M., & Every, D. (2007). The language of "race" and prejudice: A discourse of denial, reason, and liberal-practical politics. Journal of Language and Social Psychology, 26(2), 123-141. doi:10.1177/0261927X07300075</ref><ref>Capdevila, R., & Callaghan, J. (2008). ‘It’s not racist. It’s common sense’. A critical analysis of political discourse around asylum and immigration in the UK. Journal of Community & Applied Social Psychology, 18, 1–16.</ref><ref>Lynn, N., & Lea, S. (2003). ‘A phantom menace and the new apartheid’: The social construction of asylum-seekers in the United Kingdom. Discourse and Society, 14, 425–452.</ref> Discourse does not have to be explicitly racist to have discriminatory, exclusionary and oppressive effects.<ref>Wetherell, M., & Potter, J. (1992). Mapping the language of racism. London: Harvester Wheatsheaf.</ref> Downplaying race as an explanatory construct may allow for the continued [[institutionalisation]] of racial exclusion.<ref>Augoustinos, M., & Every, D. (2007). The language of "race" and prejudice: A discourse of denial, reason, and liberal-practical politics. Journal of Language and Social Psychology, 26(2), 123-141. doi:10.1177/0261927X07300075.</ref> Goodman and Burke<ref>Goodman, S., & Burke, S. (2011). Discursive deracialization in talk about asylum seeking. Journal of Community & Applied Social Psychology, 21(2), 111-123. doi:10.1002/casp.1065</ref> point out that economic, religious and incompatibility arguments are used in the discursive deracialization of opposition to [[Asylum seeker|asylum-seeking]] (in the UK). These explanatory arguments may be viewed in light of an increasing emphasis on national belonging and discourses of nation in the discursive deracialization of racist discourses.<ref>Augoustinos, M., & Every, D. (2007). The language of "race" and prejudice: A discourse of denial, reason, and liberal-practical politics. Journal of Language and Social Psychology, 26(2), 123-141. doi:10.1177/0261927X07300075.</ref>
==References== {{Reflist}}{{Sociology-stub}} [[Category:Racism]]

{{About|the crater on Mars|the lunar crater|Douglass (lunar crater)}} {{Infobox Mars crater | name = Douglass (crater) | image = DouglassMartianCrater.jpg | caption = Topo map location of Douglass Crater | coordinates = {{coord|51.8|S|70.6|W|globe:mars_type:landmark|display=inline,title}} | discoverer = | diameter = 94 km | eponym = [[Andrew E. Douglass]] }} '''Douglass''' is a crater in the east of [[Thaumasia quadrangle]] of Mars and in the east of [[Aonia Terra]], located at 51.8°S latitude and 70.6°W longitude. It is 94.0&nbsp;km in diameter and was named after [[Andrew E. Douglass]], and the name was approved in 1973.<ref>{{cite web|title=Gazetteer of Planetary Nomenclature {{!}} Douglass|url=http://planetarynames.wr.usgs.gov/Feature/1631|website=usgs.gov|publisher=[[International Astronomical Union]]|accessdate=4 March 2015}}</ref> [[File:Wikidouglasseast.jpg|thumb|left|East side of Douglass Crater, as seen by CTX camera (on [[Mars Reconnaissance Orbiter]]).]] The crater is located nearly WNW of [[Halley (Martian crater)|Halley]] and east of the ringed crater of [[Lowell (Martian crater)|Lowell]]. A third of the way to Halley is [[Ogygis Undae]] which s the only named dune field in the southern hemisphere. Further east is [[Argyre Planitia]], southwest is [[Aonia Planum]] and north is Phrixi Rupes.
