{{italic title}}
'''''Wider than the Sky: The Phenomenal Gift of Consciousness''''' is an [[English language|English-language]] [[book]] on [[neuroscience]] by the neuroscientist [[Gerald Edelman|Gerald M. Edelman]]. Yale University Press published the book in 2004 . The book includes a [[glossary]], a bibliographic note, and an [[index (publishing)|index]]. The title alludes to an English-language [[poem]] written by [[Emily Dickinson]] in about 1862 . In that poem, Dickinson describes the [[brain]] as "wider than the Sky", "deeper than the sea", and "just the weight of God".

In the preface (page xiii), Edelman describes, as follows, the purpose of the book.

{{quote|A scientific analysis of consciousness must answer the question: How can the firings of neurons give rise to subjective sensations, thoughts, and emotions? To some, the two domains are so disparate as to be irreconcilable. A scientific explanation must provide a causal account of the connection between these domains so that properties in one domain may be understood in terms of events in the other. This is the task I have set myself in this small book.}}

The book's content is similar to another one Edelman co-authored: ''[[A Universe of Consciousness|A Universe of Consciousness: How Matter Becomes Imagination]]''. Both books put forward the theory of [[neuronal group selection]], also known as [[Neural Darwinism]]. Both books make a distinction between [[primary consciousness]] and [[higher-order consciousness]].

